comments.body: All EAD physlocs of various types ("code", "text") are intermingled in ASpace, with no structured way to tell them apart. In some cases, they include additional language like "Location code:", so we can't check for string length. We probably need to string-check for the presence of hard-coded location codes.
To further complicate things, the MARC exporter concatenates all physloc notes into one 500 field.

princeton_ansible.title: Upgrade nodejs for orangelight, enable controlled upgrades generally

comments.body:
We can see the base version number now, but the `apt` task still fails, saying no version matches. The playbook should probably:
- check the installed version
- if the installed version matches the desired version, stop there
- if the installed version does not match the desired version, download node from `nodejs.org/download/release/latest-v{{ desired_version }}.x/node-v{{ desired_version }}."whatever comes next"-linux-x64.tar.gz`, then unzip and install node from that . . . but I'm not sure how to do the matching in a sustainable way (meaning, a way that works now for 16.14.0 and will still work when 16.20.8 comes out); alternatively, we could update the node version to be more specific (for example, 16.14.0 instead of 16.x)

Helpful links:
Listing of Node [releases and support schedule](https://nodejs.org/en/about/releases/)
Directory for [Node 14](https://nodejs.org/download/release/latest-v14.x/)
Directory for [Node 16](https://nodejs.org/download/release/latest-v16.x/)

Turns out they DO keep older releases on each line, see https://nodejs.org/download/release/v16.14.0/

The version we use should match https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/blob/main/.tool-versions
